  <style>
    :root {
      --terminal-bg: #0a0a0a;
      --terminal-amber: #ffb000;
      --terminal-amber-dim: #b87800;
      --terminal-amber-bright: #ffd062;
      --terminal-shadow: rgba(255, 176, 0, 0.35);
    }

    html, body {
      background: var(--terminal-bg);
    }

    .terminal-shell {
      font-family: 'VT323', 'IBM Plex Mono', 'Courier New', Courier, monospace;
      background: var(--terminal-bg);
      color: var(--terminal-amber);
      min-height: 100vh;
      padding: 1.25rem;
      text-shadow: 0 0 6px var(--terminal-shadow);
      position: relative;
      overflow-x: hidden;
    }

    /* Subtle CRT scanlines */
    .terminal-shell::before {
      content: '';
      position: fixed;
      inset: 0;
      pointer-events: none;
      background: repeating-linear-gradient(
        to bottom,
        rgba(0, 0, 0, 0) 0px,
        rgba(0, 0, 0, 0) 2px,
        rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.18) 3px,
        rgba(0, 0, 0, 0) 4px
      );
      z-index: 9999;
      mix-blend-mode: multiply;
    }

    .terminal-shell::after {
      content: '';
      position: fixed;
      inset: 0;
      pointer-events: none;
      background: radial-gradient(ellipse at center, transparent 55%, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.55) 100%);
      z-index: 9998;
    }

    .terminal-frame {
      max-width: 880px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      border: 2px solid var(--terminal-amber-dim);
      padding: 1rem 1.25rem 1.5rem;
      box-shadow: 0 0 18px var(--terminal-shadow), inset 0 0 24px rgba(255, 176, 0, 0.08);
      position: relative;
      z-index: 1;
    }

    .terminal-header {
      display: flex;
      justify-content: space-between;
      align-items: center;
      border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--terminal-amber-dim);
      padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
      margin-bottom: 1rem;
      font-size: 1rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.08em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
    }

    .terminal-header .status-block {
      color: var(--terminal-amber-bright);
    }

    .ascii-banner {
      white-space: pre;
      line-height: 1;
      color: var(--terminal-amber-bright);
      font-size: 0.78rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.02em;
      margin-bottom: 1rem;
      overflow-x: auto;
    }

    .scene-meta {
      font-size: 1rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.18em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      color: var(--terminal-amber-dim);
      margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    }

    .scene-text {
      font-size: 1.35rem;
      line-height: 1.55;
      min-height: 12em;
      white-space: pre-wrap;
      margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
    }

    .scene-text .blink {
      display: inline-block;
      width: 0.55em;
      height: 1.05em;
      background: var(--terminal-amber);
      margin-left: 2px;
      vertical-align: -0.15em;
      animation: blink 1.05s steps(2) infinite;
    }

    @keyframes blink {
      to { opacity: 0; }
    }

    .choices-list {
      list-style: none;
      padding: 0;
      margin: 0 0 1rem;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: 0.35rem;
    }

    .choice-button {
      background: transparent;
      border: 1px solid var(--terminal-amber-dim);
      color: var(--terminal-amber);
      font-family: inherit;
      font-size: 1.15rem;
      padding: 0.65rem 0.9rem;
      width: 100%;
      text-align: left;
      cursor: pointer;
      text-shadow: 0 0 6px var(--terminal-shadow);
      transition: background 90ms linear, color 90ms linear, transform 90ms ease-out;
    }

    .choice-button:hover,
    .choice-button:focus-visible {
      background: var(--terminal-amber);
      color: #1a0e00;
      outline: none;
      transform: translateX(4px);
    }

    .choice-button:disabled {
      opacity: 0.4;
      cursor: not-allowed;
      transform: none;
    }

    .footer-bar {
      display: flex;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      gap: 1rem;
      justify-content: space-between;
      align-items: center;
      border-top: 1px dashed var(--terminal-amber-dim);
      padding-top: 0.75rem;
      margin-top: 1rem;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
    }

    .footer-bar button {
      background: transparent;
      border: 1px solid var(--terminal-amber-dim);
      color: var(--terminal-amber);
      font-family: inherit;
      padding: 0.4rem 0.8rem;
      cursor: pointer;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
    }

    .footer-bar button:hover,
    .footer-bar button:focus-visible {
      background: var(--terminal-amber);
      color: #1a0e00;
      outline: none;
    }

    .ending-summary {
      border: 1px solid var(--terminal-amber);
      padding: 0.9rem 1rem;
      margin: 1rem 0;
      background: rgba(255, 176, 0, 0.04);
    }

    .ending-summary h3 {
      margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.15em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
    }

    .stat-row {
      display: flex;
      justify-content: space-between;
      gap: 1rem;
      font-size: 1rem;
    }

    .stat-bar {
      flex: 1;
      height: 0.65em;
      background: rgba(255, 176, 0, 0.12);
      border: 1px solid var(--terminal-amber-dim);
      overflow: hidden;
      align-self: center;
    }

    .stat-bar > span {
      display: block;
      height: 100%;
      background: var(--terminal-amber);
    }

    .skip-link {
      position: absolute;
      left: -9999px;
      top: 0;
      color: #1a0e00;
      background: var(--terminal-amber);
      padding: 0.4rem 0.8rem;
      z-index: 10000;
    }

    .skip-link:focus {
      left: 1rem;
      top: 1rem;
    }

    @media (max-width: 600px) {
      .scene-text { font-size: 1.15rem; }
      .choice-button { font-size: 1rem; }
      .ascii-banner { font-size: 0.55rem; }
      .terminal-frame { padding: 0.75rem; }
    }

    @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
      .scene-text .blink { animation: none; }
      .choice-button { transition: none; }
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <a href="#scene" class="skip-link">Skip to game</a>
  <div class="terminal-shell" role="main">
    <div class="terminal-frame" aria-live="polite">
      <div class="terminal-header">
        <span>COCO-DOS v2.0</span>
        <span class="status-block" id="status-block">READY</span>
      </div>

      <pre class="ascii-banner" aria-hidden="true">
   ____  _ _ _                ____
  / ___|(_) (_) ___ ___  _ __ |  _ \ _ __ ___  __ _ _ __ ___  ___
  \___ \| | | |/ __/ _ \| '_ \| | | | '__/ _ \/ _` | '_ ` _ \/ __|
   ___) | | | | (_| (_) | | | | |_| | | |  __/ (_| | | | | | \__ \
  |____/|_|_|_|\___\___/|_| |_|____/|_|  \___|\__,_|_| |_| |_|___/
        A Coffee &amp; Fun text adventure — 1971 to 2025
      </pre>

      <div class="scene-meta" id="scene-meta">SYSTEM // BOOT</div>
      <div class="scene-text" id="scene-text" tabindex="-1" aria-atomic="true">Loading...</div>

      <ul class="choices-list" id="choices" aria-label="Choices"></ul>

      <div class="footer-bar">
        <span id="progress-block" aria-live="polite">SCENE 0</span>
        <div>
          <button type="button" id="skip-btn" aria-label="Skip typewriter animation">SKIP</button>
          <button type="button" id="restart-btn" aria-label="Restart adventure">RESTART</button>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <noscript>
      <div style="max-width:880px;margin:1rem auto;border:2px solid #b87800;padding:1rem;color:#ffb000;font-family:'Courier New',monospace;">
        <h2>Silicon Dreams</h2>
        <p>This is a text adventure RPG about the founding of Apple, Microsoft, and Google. Enable JavaScript to play.</p>
        <p>It's a 15-20 minute playthrough. Your choices, based on real historical events, decide whether you become Steve Jobs, Bill Gates, Larry Page — or the teacher who inspired them all.</p>
      </div>
    </noscript>
  </div>

  <script>
    (function() {
      'use strict';

      const SCENES = {
        intro: {
          meta: 'PALO ALTO // 1971',
          text: "You are sixteen years old.\n\nThe Vietnam War mumbles from the television in the next room. Your father is yelling at Walter Cronkite. Your mother is yelling at your father. None of this matters.\n\nWhat matters is the issue of POPULAR ELECTRONICS open on your desk, the soldering iron warming up beside it, and the bag of components you bought with three weeks of paper-route money from Hal's Electronics on El Camino.\n\nYou are not yet anyone. But somewhere in this room — in this state, in this decade — you are going to choose.",
          choices: [
            { label: 'Read about Intel\'s new 4004 microprocessor', next: 'popular_electronics', effects: { microsoft: 1, google: 1 } },
            { label: 'Sneak out to the HP Explorers Club meeting tonight', next: 'blue_box', effects: { apple: 2 } },
            { label: 'Help your little sister Maya with her algebra', next: 'sister_algebra', effects: { teacher: 2 } }
          ]
        },

        popular_electronics: {
          meta: 'YOUR BEDROOM // LATE EVENING',
          text: "The article is electric. Intel has crammed an entire central processing unit onto a single chip the size of your thumbnail. Two thousand three hundred transistors. Eight hundred kilohertz. They are calling it 'a microcomputer on a chip.'\n\nYou read it three times. Then a fourth. The chip costs sixty dollars. Sixty dollars. You have nineteen dollars and a paper route.\n\nWalter Cronkite has finished. Your father has gone quiet. You have decisions.",
          choices: [
            { label: 'Save every paper-route dollar; order the chip and BUILD something', next: 'crossroads_1975', effects: { apple: 2, microsoft: 1 } },
            { label: 'Write Intel directly. Ask — politely, professionally — for a free sample', next: 'crossroads_1975', effects: { microsoft: 2, google: 1 } },
            { label: 'Bring the article to your math teacher. You need help understanding it', next: 'crossroads_1975', effects: { teacher: 2, google: 1 } }
          ]
        },

        blue_box: {
          meta: 'HEWLETT-PACKARD CAMPUS // PALO ALTO',
          text: "The Explorers Club meeting room smells like solder, instant coffee, and teenage ambition.\n\nA tall, lanky engineer-in-training named Steve is holding court over a small blue plastic box. He's a few years older than you. Sandals. Bad haircut. Eyes that don't blink enough.\n\n'It's a blue box,' he says. 'You hold it to the phone receiver. It generates the 2600-hertz tone. The whole AT&T long-distance switching system thinks you're an operator. You can call anywhere on Earth for free. Watch.'\n\nHe dials the Vatican. He asks for the Pope. He almost gets through.\n\nThen he turns and shoves the device into your hands. 'Want to try?'",
          choices: [
            { label: 'Call the Pope. Worst case you make a story you tell forever', next: 'crossroads_1975', effects: { apple: 3 } },
            { label: 'Politely decline — stealing from AT&T is still stealing', next: 'crossroads_1975', effects: { teacher: 2, google: 1 } },
            { label: 'Ask him how it works — and whether you can build one', next: 'crossroads_1975', effects: { apple: 2, microsoft: 1 } }
          ]
        },

        sister_algebra: {
          meta: 'KITCHEN TABLE // 9:14 PM',
          text: "Maya is eleven. Her textbook is open to quadratics. She is, in her own words, 'absolutely going to fail.'\n\nYou sit down with her. You ask her to tell you what the question is ASKING — not how to solve it. She thinks for a long time. Then she explains it. Then she solves it.\n\n'I just needed someone to slow down,' she says. She is crying a little, the relieved kind.\n\nSomething happens in your chest that you do not have a word for yet. It is the feeling of being useful in a way no computer can be.\n\nUpstairs, your soldering iron is still warm.",
          choices: [
            { label: 'Stay. Tutor her in everything. The chips can wait', next: 'crossroads_1975', effects: { teacher: 3 } },
            { label: 'Show her how a computer could solve EVERY quadratic, ever', next: 'crossroads_1975', effects: { teacher: 1, google: 2 } },
            { label: 'Start sketching a "teaching machine" that quizzes students', next: 'crossroads_1975', effects: { teacher: 2, microsoft: 1 } }
          ]
        },

        crossroads_1975: {
          meta: 'A CROSSROADS // JANUARY 1975',
          text: "Four years have passed.\n\nThe new POPULAR ELECTRONICS lands in your mailbox. On the cover: the MITS Altair 8800. World's first personal computer kit. Three hundred ninety-seven dollars. No keyboard. No monitor. No software. Just switches and lights and a promise.\n\nYou are twenty. You can feel the whole future cracking open like an egg.\n\nWhere do you go?",
          choices: [
            { label: 'Drop out of school. Head east to Boston. Write software for the Altair', next: 'altair_basic', effects: { microsoft: 4 } },
            { label: 'Drive to Menlo Park. There\'s a new club called Homebrew. Be there Wednesday', next: 'homebrew_meeting', effects: { apple: 4 } },
            { label: 'Take the Stanford acceptance letter. Study computer science properly', next: 'stanford_meeting', effects: { google: 4 } },
            { label: 'Stay home. Apply for the teaching job at Cupertino Junior High', next: 'first_class', effects: { teacher: 4 } }
          ]
        },

        // ===== APPLE PATH =====

        homebrew_meeting: {
          meta: 'GORDON FRENCH\'S GARAGE // MENLO PARK',
          text: "Thirty-two people. Folding chairs. A mimeographed newsletter. Someone is showing off a paper-tape reader they soldered onto an Altair. Someone else is playing a tinny version of 'Fool on the Hill' through a speaker hooked to a computer.\n\nA tall thin guy in jeans and sandals introduces himself as Woz. He's holding up a single-board computer he hand-soldered using the cheap MOS 6502 chip instead of the expensive Intel 8080.\n\n'I was going to give the schematics away,' he says, sheepish. 'My friend Steve thinks I should sell it.'\n\nSteve is standing next to him. You know that face. You've met him before, by a phone, in a Vatican kind of way.\n\nWoz looks at you. 'What do you think?'",
          choices: [
            { label: '"Woz, you\'re a genius. SELL IT. Charge what it\'s worth"', next: 'garage_pitch', effects: { apple: 3 } },
            { label: '"Take the schematics. I\'ll go home and build my own"', next: 'garage_pitch', effects: { apple: 1, microsoft: 2 } },
            { label: '"Write the manual first. Teach kids to build these"', next: 'garage_pitch', effects: { apple: 1, teacher: 3 } }
          ]
        },

        garage_pitch: {
          meta: 'CRIST DRIVE GARAGE // LOS ALTOS',
          text: "It's a few weeks later. You're sitting on a folding chair in the Jobs family garage. Woz is hunched over a workbench, soldering with the precision of a watchmaker. Steve is pacing. Steve is always pacing.\n\n'We need capital,' he says. 'I'll sell my Volkswagen bus. Woz is selling his HP-65 calculator. That gets us thirteen hundred bucks. We need a third.'\n\nHe stops. He looks at you. He is doing the eye thing.\n\n'Are you in?'",
          choices: [
            { label: '"I\'m in. I\'ll sell my car"', next: 'byte_shop', effects: { apple: 3 } },
            { label: '"I\'m in — IF we incorporate properly and split the equity in writing"', next: 'byte_shop', effects: { apple: 1, microsoft: 2 } },
            { label: '"I\'ll help part-time. I have a teaching contract starting Monday"', next: 'byte_shop', effects: { apple: 1, teacher: 2 } }
          ]
        },

        byte_shop: {
          meta: 'THE BYTE SHOP // MOUNTAIN VIEW',
          text: "Paul Terrell, the owner, looks at the bare Apple I board. He had been expecting a fully-assembled, ready-to-use computer in a wooden case.\n\n'You boys want to sell me a circuit board with no case, no keyboard, no power supply,' he says, 'and you want how much for it?'\n\nSteve says, without flinching: 'Six hundred sixty-six dollars and sixty-six cents.'\n\nPaul stares. Then he says — and you will remember this sentence for the rest of your life — 'I'll take fifty.'\n\nYou now have to build fifty Apple I computers in thirty days. Out of a garage. With three people. Steve looks at you, eyebrows up.",
          choices: [
            { label: '"Call every parent, friend, and ex-girlfriend. Build a soldering line"', next: 'apple_climax', effects: { apple: 3 } },
            { label: '"Hire someone professional. We need a real assembly process"', next: 'apple_climax', effects: { apple: 1, microsoft: 2 } },
            { label: '"Bring in high school kids — pay them, teach them, build the company AROUND them"', next: 'apple_climax', effects: { apple: 1, teacher: 3 } }
          ]
        },

        apple_climax: {
          meta: 'BACKSTAGE // FLINT CENTER // JAN 24, 1984',
          text: "It's been eight years.\n\nIn three minutes you will walk on stage. Steve will pull a Macintosh out of a canvas bag, hit return, and let it introduce itself. The TV ad — the one with the woman and the hammer and Big Brother — has already aired during the Super Bowl. Thirty-five million people are about to meet a computer.\n\nSteve turns to you, suddenly small. His hands are shaking.\n\n'Are we doing the right thing?' he asks. 'IBM has a hundred times our budget. They're going to crush us. Maybe we should have just made better Apple IIs.'\n\nWhat do you say?",
          choices: [
            { label: '"We make a dent in the universe. Or we go down trying"', next: 'ending_apple' },
            { label: '"Maybe — but a partnership with IBM right now could save us all"', next: 'ending_microsoft' },
            { label: '"Win or lose, our real legacy is the people who learn from this"', next: 'ending_teacher' }
          ]
        },

        // ===== MICROSOFT PATH =====

        altair_basic: {
          meta: 'AIKEN COMPUTATION LAB // HARVARD',
          text: "You arrive in Cambridge in February of '75 with a duffel bag and forty dollars. The wind off the Charles River is trying to take your face off.\n\nIn a basement lab full of PDP-10 mainframes, you find them: a scrawny Harvard sophomore named Bill, and his older friend Paul. Bill is rocking back and forth in his chair, the way he always does. Paul is calmer. They have a plan.\n\n'We're going to write a BASIC interpreter for the Altair,' Bill says. 'We don't own one. We've never SEEN one. We have eight weeks before someone else does it.'\n\nPaul nods. 'We need a third programmer.'\n\nBill says: 'Are you in?'",
          choices: [
            { label: '"I\'m in. Eight weeks. We don\'t sleep"', next: 'albuquerque', effects: { microsoft: 3 } },
            { label: '"I\'ll help debug — but I\'m not dropping out of college over this"', next: 'albuquerque', effects: { microsoft: 1, teacher: 2 } },
            { label: '"Open-source it. Information wants to be free, Bill"', next: 'albuquerque', effects: { microsoft: 1, apple: 2 } }
          ]
        },

        albuquerque: {
          meta: 'MITS HEADQUARTERS // ALBUQUERQUE, NM',
          text: "Eight weeks. No sleep. The interpreter runs on the very first try when Paul demonstrates it to Ed Roberts at MITS — and the audience watches a computer ASK the Altair to compute two plus two, and the Altair answers FOUR.\n\nIt is April 4, 1975. You, Bill, and Paul are standing under the New Mexico sun, signing the incorporation paperwork for a tiny new company called Micro-Soft. The hyphen will go in a year.\n\nBill turns to you. 'We need an answer to one question before we sign. What is this company?'",
          choices: [
            { label: '"A software company. We license code. We never give it away"', next: 'ibm_deal', effects: { microsoft: 3 } },
            { label: '"A platform company. The OS is the only thing that matters long-term"', next: 'ibm_deal', effects: { microsoft: 3, google: 1 } },
            { label: '"A teaching company. Every product ships with a tutorial"', next: 'ibm_deal', effects: { microsoft: 1, teacher: 3 } }
          ]
        },

        ibm_deal: {
          meta: 'MICROSOFT // BELLEVUE // JULY 1980',
          text: "Three men in blue suits arrive from Boca Raton, Florida. They will not say what they want. They make everyone sign non-disclosure agreements thicker than a phone book.\n\nThe men work for IBM. IBM is building a secret personal computer. They need an operating system. They have come to Microsoft because Bill's mother knows a man on the IBM board.\n\nBut here's the problem: Microsoft does not HAVE an operating system. You don't write operating systems. You write BASIC.\n\nIn the next room, Bill is hyperventilating. You happen to know about a guy named Tim Paterson up the road in Seattle who's written a thing called QDOS — 'Quick and Dirty Operating System.' Bill asks: 'What do we do?'",
          choices: [
            { label: '"Buy QDOS for $50K. License it to IBM. KEEP. THE. RIGHTS"', next: 'microsoft_climax', effects: { microsoft: 4 } },
            { label: '"Tell IBM the truth. We don\'t have it yet. Negotiate honestly"', next: 'microsoft_climax', effects: { microsoft: 1, teacher: 3 } },
            { label: '"Walk away. IBM will swallow us whole"', next: 'microsoft_climax', effects: { apple: 2, microsoft: 1 } }
          ]
        },

        microsoft_climax: {
          meta: 'WINDOWS 95 LAUNCH // REDMOND // AUGUST 24, 1995',
          text: "The Rolling Stones are blaring 'Start Me Up' through speakers the size of refrigerators. Jay Leno is on the stage. There are eight thousand people on the Microsoft campus. Cars are double-parked on the freeway. People in Tokyo are queueing at midnight for boxed copies.\n\nBill is wearing a tie, which is unusual. He has tucked his shirt in, which is unprecedented.\n\nHe leans over to you, just out of the microphone's range.\n\n'We won, didn't we?' he says. 'We actually won.'\n\nWhat do you tell him?",
          choices: [
            { label: '"We won. We put a personal computer in every home on Earth"', next: 'ending_microsoft' },
            { label: '"We won the OS war. Now figure out what to do with the power"', next: 'ending_teacher' },
